<Wizard::IntroContent
  @setupTime="30 min"
  @description="Policies govern the behavior of all users, tokens, and entities by defining the rules (ACLs) that explicitly grant or forbid access to specific paths and operations within Vault."
  @imageAlt="namespace hierarchy example"
  @imageCaption="Policy works as a checkpoint to determine userâ€™s privileges to access operations or secrets inside Vault."
  @imageSrc={{img-path "~/acl-policies-intro.png"}}
>
  <:features>
    <Wizard::IntroContent::Feature @icon="service">
      Ensure the principle of
      <strong>least privilege</strong>, so that users and applications can only access specific secrets and configuration
      paths necessary for their core function.
    </Wizard::IntroContent::Feature>
    <Wizard::IntroContent::Feature @icon="globe">
      In multi-tenant environments, policies apply
      <strong>hierarchically</strong>. A policy created in a child namespace manages paths only in that namespace.
    </Wizard::IntroContent::Feature>
    <Wizard::IntroContent::Feature @icon="lock">
      You'll need a
      <strong>privileged token</strong>
      (such as Root) to write the policy governing the whole cluster.
    </Wizard::IntroContent::Feature>
  </:features>
</Wizard::IntroContent>